Dialogue: 1,0:00:00.82,0:00:14.77,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}Hi welcome back to part two of my extended director's cut of my GDC talk on 30 puzzle design lessons from classic puzzle communities and how those lessons can be applied to the creation of video game puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.82,0:00:14.77,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}大家好，欢迎回到我的GDC演讲"来自经典谜题社区的30节谜题设计课， \N 以及如何将这些经验应用到电子游戏谜题的创作中"的第二部分
Dialogue: 1,0:00:14.77,0:00:18.61,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}The 11th lesson is “create a rewarding ending”
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.77,0:00:18.61,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}第11节课是「创造一个有收获的结局」
Dialogue: 1,0:00:18.61,0:00:23.73,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and the quintessential example of this is the puzzle Picross aka Nanograms
Dialogue: 0,0:00:18.61,0:00:23.73,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这方面最典型的例子是Picross，也就是"数织"游戏
Dialogue: 2,0:00:20.60,0:00:24.70,Annote,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（译者注：Nanogram数织游戏，在一个空白网格中，每行每列前面都标注有该行或该列中连续相邻黑格的长度，玩家据此来涂色）
Dialogue: 1,0:00:23.73,0:00:27.70,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}which the Picross games have been published by Nintendo since the 90s
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.73,0:00:27.70,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}任天堂从90年代开始发行Picross游戏
Dialogue: 1,0:00:27.70,0:00:33.40,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and I think the first nanograms were published in the late 80s in various Japanese puzzle magazines.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.70,0:00:33.40,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而我认为第一个数织游戏是在80年代末发表在各种日本解谜杂志上的
Dialogue: 1,0:00:33.40,0:00:36.21,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}There's an interesting story about the origin of them.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.40,0:00:36.21,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}关于它的起源有一个有趣的故事
Dialogue: 2,0:00:36.21,0:00:40.56,Annote,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（译者注：由 西尾徹也 和 いしだのん 二人独立创作）
Dialogue: 1,0:00:36.21,0:00:40.56,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}They were created by two different authors seemingly simultaneously,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.21,0:00:40.56,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}数织是由两个不同作者独立创造的
Dialogue: 1,0:00:40.56,0:00:45.24,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but alas one of the exciting things about nanograms is at the end you sort of get this picture
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.56,0:00:45.24,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}数织游戏令人兴奋的一点是，在最后你会得到这样的图案
Dialogue: 1,0:00:45.24,0:00:48.24,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and there's always this question like what is the picture gonna be,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.24,0:00:48.24,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（在解的过程中）总会产生比如"这个图案会是什么呢？"的问题
Dialogue: 1,0:00:48.24,0:00:51.96,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}anticipation for uh sort of that exciting moment
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.24,0:00:51.96,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}对那个激动人心的时刻有一种期盼
Dialogue: 1,0:00:51.96,0:00:59.00,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}where the picture or the identity of the picture, What is it? Oh, it's a rubber duck! It's a lion! It’s finally revealed.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.96,0:00:59.00,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这个图案或图案代表的是什么呢？哦，是一只橡皮鸭！是一只狮子！最终终于被揭开了
Dialogue: 1,0:00:59.00,0:01:06.16,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}Another example is this puzzle Spiral Galaxies which it doesn't have an ending surprise step at the end
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.00,0:01:06.16,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}另一个例子是"螺旋星系"谜题，它本身是没有一个惊喜的结尾的
Dialogue: 1,0:01:06.16,0:01:10.84,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but a variant of it does and I will show you the classic first
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.16,0:01:10.84,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但它的一个变体却有，我先给你们看经典版本
Dialogue: 1,0:01:10.84,0:01:12.88,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}So, this is the classic spiral galaxies.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.84,0:01:12.88,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这就是经典版本的螺旋星系
Dialogue: 1,0:01:12.88,0:01:16.02,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}The goal is to partition the grid into these regions,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.88,0:01:16.02,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}游戏目标是将网格划分为一些区域
Dialogue: 1,0:01:16.02,0:01:23.96,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}each of which contains exactly one dot and the shape of the region is rotationally symmetric 180 degrees around that dot.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.02,0:01:23.96,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}每个区域正好包含一个点，而且每个区域围绕那个点中心对称
Dialogue: 1,0:01:23.96,0:01:25.62,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}It's a very interesting puzzle.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.96,0:01:25.62,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是一个非常有趣的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:01:25.62,0:01:29.46,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}There's a lot of fascinating logic that goes into solving them.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.62,0:01:29.46,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}深入研究的话就会有很多迷人的逻辑
Dialogue: 1,0:01:29.46,0:01:35.80,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}But another similar type of puzzle which is printed by Nikoli under the name “Tentai Show”
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.46,0:01:35.80,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}不过有一种类似的谜题，是Nikoli以"Tentai show"的名字刊发的
Dialogue: 1,0:01:35.80,0:01:38.48,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}which is a hilarious pun if you know Japanese.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.80,0:01:38.48,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你懂日语的话，（"Tentai Show"）这个名字还是个滑稽的双关
Dialogue: 1,0:01:38.48,0:01:42.77,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}“taishou” means symmetry and ten means symmetry about a point
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.48,0:01:42.77,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}「点」(ten)是点的意思，「対称」(taishou）是对称的意思，合起来就是点对称
Dialogue: 1,0:01:42.77,0:01:50.71,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but “tentai” also means sort of a heavenly body like a galaxy, so, this is a show of heavenly bodies.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.77,0:01:50.71,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但「天体」(tentai)又是天体的意思，所以，这又是"天体show"
Dialogue: 1,0:01:50.71,0:01:52.82,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}Excellent pun.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.71,0:01:52.82,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}很棒的双关
Dialogue: 1,0:01:52.82,0:01:54.55,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}Anyways digression
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.82,0:01:54.55,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}无论如何，有点跑题了
Dialogue: 1,0:01:54.55,0:01:59.86,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}this was first published in Nikoli magazine in 2001 by an author who goes by Gesaku
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.55,0:01:59.86,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这个在2001年首次发表在Nikoli杂志上的作品，作者叫Gesaku
Dialogue: 1,0:01:59.86,0:02:04.08,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and it's essentially a spiral galaxy's puzzle where some of the dots are dark colored
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.86,0:02:04.08,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它本质上还是一个螺旋星系谜题，不过其中一些点是涂黑了的
Dialogue: 1,0:02:04.08,0:02:07.54,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and if you shade the dark colored dots, you get a shape
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.08,0:02:07.54,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你把黑点对应的区域上色的话，就会得到一个形状
Dialogue: 1,0:02:07.54,0:02:11.00,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and here's a more sophisticated example quite a large instance
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.54,0:02:11.00,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这里有一个更复杂的例子，相当大的一个例子
Dialogue: 1,0:02:11.00,0:02:16.37,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}when you solve it, you get this and the shape is that of an astronaut
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.00,0:02:16.37,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}当你解出来的时候，你会得到一个宇航员的图形
Dialogue: 1,0:02:16.37,0:02:20.34,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh quite an interesting uh composition that's been put together
Dialogue: 0,0:02:16.37,0:02:20.34,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}非常有趣的构图
Dialogue: 1,0:02:20.34,0:02:23.09,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and you might ask well is the puzzle boring because of this
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.34,0:02:23.09,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你可能会问，这样做了之后谜题会不会变得无聊？
Dialogue: 1,0:02:23.09,0:02:29.81,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}does this sort of compromise the flow of the puzzle because you're having to make all of these regions fit together in exactly this way
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.09,0:02:29.81,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是否会牺牲解谜过程，因为必须得让这些区域按图形这种方式组合在一起
Dialogue: 1,0:02:29.81,0:02:31.28,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and the answer is mostly not
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.81,0:02:31.28,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}答案是大部分不会
Dialogue: 1,0:02:31.28,0:02:38.96,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like if you look over to the left side of this puzzle, you can kind of see there's really elaborate snaking and winding regions going all over the place
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.28,0:02:38.96,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你看一下这个谜题的左边，你可以看到有一些精心设计的蜿蜒曲折的区域
Dialogue: 1,0:02:38.96,0:02:44.60,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and those are quite interesting to solve and to sort of figure out the logic of how that must be shaped
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.96,0:02:44.60,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这些解起来都很有趣，而且弄清楚形状形成的逻辑也很有趣
Dialogue: 1,0:02:44.60,0:02:52.08,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}however, putting those in sort of requires large amounts of just one color of region
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.60,0:02:52.08,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然而，把这些形状融入进去就会让很多区域是同一种颜色
Dialogue: 1,0:02:52.08,0:02:54.71,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and that can sort of force the design
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.08,0:02:54.71,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这可能会影响到设计
Dialogue: 1,0:02:54.71,0:03:02.39,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}if you wanted to make a qr code into this then probably most of the puzzle would be relatively uninteresting to solve
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.71,0:03:02.39,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你想弄成个二维码图案的谜题，那么谜题大部分解起来就会相对无趣了
Dialogue: 1,0:03:02.39,0:03:07.96,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it relies or depends heavily on uh the shape being a certain way
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.39,0:03:07.96,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这在很大程度上依赖于形状本身
Dialogue: 1,0:03:07.96,0:03:10.20,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}here's an example that kind of illustrates that
Dialogue: 0,0:03:07.96,0:03:10.20,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这里有一个例子可以说明这一点
Dialogue: 1,0:03:10.20,0:03:15.64,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}this is you know I’m just putting this together to show off its GDC 2021
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.20,0:03:15.64,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这个是我做的一个展现出GDC2021的图案
Dialogue: 2,0:03:15.64,0:03:20.69,Annote,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（译者注：用文本生成Tentai Show谜题的生成器在：https://erikdemaine.org/fonts/spiralgalaxies/）
Dialogue: 1,0:03:15.64,0:03:20.69,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but this is actually made using a text generator by Erik Demaine and Martin Demaine
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.64,0:03:20.69,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我这个实际上是用Erik Demaine和Martin Demaine的文本生成器来生成的
Dialogue: 1,0:03:20.69,0:03:23.89,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and it shows you know you can do whatever you want with these Tentai Show puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.69,0:03:23.89,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这个就表面了你可以用任何图案来制作Tentai Show谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:03:23.89,0:03:28.44,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but like you know this is the 2 and it's just a diagonal set of one by one things
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.89,0:03:28.44,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但你看这是个2，它只是一个一个点斜着摆放而已
Dialogue: 1,0:03:28.44,0:03:34.13,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's not particularly interesting or solve or fun to solve
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.44,0:03:34.13,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这个解起来并不是特别有趣
Dialogue: 1,0:03:34.13,0:03:36.56,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}another example of putting a surprise at the end of the puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.13,0:03:36.56,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}另一个在谜题结尾加入惊喜的例子是
Dialogue: 1,0:03:36.56,0:03:40.60,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}are the extraction steps that occur in puzzle hunts like the MIT mystery hunt
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.56,0:03:40.60,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}在解谜寻宝比赛中的"提炼步骤"，比如MIT解谜寻宝比赛
Dialogue: 2,0:03:40.60,0:03:46.74,Annote,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（译者注：元谜题 meta puzzle，几个谜题的答案本身又组成一个新的谜题）
Dialogue: 1,0:03:40.60,0:03:46.74,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}where every single puzzle has a solution that is a word or a phrase and often those are used in metapuzzles or other things
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.60,0:03:46.74,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}在那里面每道谜题的答案都是一个单词或短语，而这些答案又常被用于"元谜题"之类的东西
Dialogue: 1,0:03:46.74,0:03:51.22,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}here's a Tentai show puzzle whose answer is actually a five letter word
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.74,0:03:51.22,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这里有一道Tentai Show谜题，它的答案是一个五个字母的单词
Dialogue: 1,0:03:51.22,0:03:56.28,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and if you solve it, you get this and maybe you can guess what the five letter word answer is
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.22,0:03:56.28,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你解开它，你会得到这样一个图案，那么你也许能猜出这个答案是什么
Dialogue: 1,0:03:56.28,0:03:58.32,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}of course, it is clubs
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.28,0:03:58.32,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}当然，答案是"梅花♣"
Dialogue: 2,0:03:58.32,0:04:01.97,Annote,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（译者注：pavelspuzzles.com/aenigmas/）
Dialogue: 1,0:03:58.32,0:04:01.97,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}this is by Pavel Curtis from his blog Adalogical Ænigmas
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.32,0:04:01.97,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这个谜题是来自Pavel Curtis的博客Adalogical Ænigmas
Dialogue: 1,0:04:01.97,0:04:06.90,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}which has a lot of interesting puzzles that have a word or phrase as an answer
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.97,0:04:06.90,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}他有很多用一个单词或短语作为答案的有趣的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:04:06.90,0:04:10.42,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}the extraction steps have a couple of values
Dialogue: 0,0:04:06.90,0:04:10.42,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}"提炼步骤"有几个方面的价值
Dialogue: 1,0:04:10.42,0:04:17.08,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}they provide this additional final eureka moment which can be especially exciting if you're anticipating it or there's a little bit of a surprise at the end
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.42,0:04:17.08,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它们提供了最后这样一个额外的尤里卡时刻，如果你期待它出现的话，那么它会非常令人兴奋
Dialogue: 1,0:04:17.08,0:04:28.60,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}they also exploit the peak end rule which means uh well the the things that people tend to remember the most are are sort of the the peak or the most salient part of an experience as well as the ending or the last thing
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.08,0:04:28.60,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它们还利用了「峰终定律(Peak-End Rule)」： \N 人们倾向于记住一段体验中的高峰或最突出的部分，以及结尾部分
Dialogue: 1,0:04:28.60,0:04:31.80,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and so, if the last part of an experience is somehow exciting or memorable
Dialogue: 0,0:04:28.60,0:04:31.80,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因此，如果一个体验的结尾部分是令人激动或难忘的话，
Dialogue: 1,0:04:31.80,0:04:35.70,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}then overall the experience will be viewed more positively
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.80,0:04:35.70,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那么总体来说，这个体验会被更加积极地看待
Dialogue: 1,0:04:35.70,0:04:38.07,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and so that's true of puzzles like these
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.70,0:04:38.07,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而谜题也是如此
Dialogue: 1,0:04:38.07,0:04:45.49,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it also can create setups for metapuzzles where words like clubs can be used as ingredients in another puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.07,0:04:45.49,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它还能为元谜题创造条件，像"梅花"这样的单词可以被用作另一个谜题的成分
Dialogue: 1,0:04:45.49,0:04:47.82,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and many uh puzzle hunts like MIT mystery hunter 
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.49,0:04:47.82,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而许多解谜寻宝比赛，比如MIT解谜寻宝比赛，
Dialogue: 1,0:04:47.82,0:04:50.87,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}set up with these meta puzzles that are sort of like boss puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.82,0:04:50.87,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}会设置这样的元谜题来作为类似说最后的Boss谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:04:50.87,0:04:56.76,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}where there might be 12 other puzzles you need to solve and then you take those 12 words and you use them to solve this final puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.87,0:04:56.76,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你可能得先解决另外12个谜题，然后拿着这12个单词来解决这最后的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:04:56.76,0:04:59.89,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and maybe only eight to ten of those twelve are actually needed
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.76,0:04:59.89,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}或者也许实际上只需要其中8到10个单词
Dialogue: 1,0:04:59.89,0:05:07.70,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, uh it can create a sort of progression gate where you don't necessarily need to solve everything but you need to solve most of it
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.89,0:05:07.70,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以这样可以创造一种阶段性门槛，你不一定得解决全部谜题，可能解决其中大部分就行了
Dialogue: 1,0:05:07.70,0:05:12.24,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um and that can be very useful for uh pacing and structuring a puzzle hunt
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.70,0:05:12.24,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这对于设置解谜寻宝比赛的节奏和步骤非常有用
Dialogue: 1,0:05:12.63,0:05:16.21,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}lesson number 12 is to embed secrets and surprises
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.63,0:05:16.21,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}第12课是「藏入一些秘密和惊喜」
Dialogue: 1,0:05:16.21,0:05:20.05,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and this is sort of another way of cramming more eureka moments into the same puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.21,0:05:20.05,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这算是向同一道谜题中塞入更多尤里卡时刻的另一种方式
Dialogue: 2,0:05:20.05,0:05:22.74,Annote,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（译者注：Cryptic Crossword是一种在英国特别流行的填字游戏，其中每个词的线索都是一个字谜）
Dialogue: 1,0:05:20.05,0:05:22.74,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I’ll show you one example from cryptic crosswords
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.05,0:05:22.74,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我给你看一个Cryptic Crossword的例子
Dialogue: 1,0:05:22.74,0:05:28.82,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}these things are called Ninas and they are sort of little easter eggs hidden in a puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.74,0:05:28.82,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这种东西被称作「Nina」，它们算是藏在谜题中的小彩蛋
Dialogue: 1,0:05:28.82,0:05:33.04,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}in this puzzle if you read the words going around the outside or the letters it will say
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.82,0:05:33.04,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}在这道谜题中，如果你把沿着外框周围的字母按顺序读出来就是：
Dialogue: 1,0:05:33.04,0:05:41.30,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}"Monty Python’s Flying Circus" , sort of going sequentially around the border of the puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.04,0:05:41.30,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}"Monty Python's Flying Circus"（《巨蟒剧团之飞翔的马戏团》）
Dialogue: 1,0:05:41.30,0:05:42.90,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and this is known as a Nina
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.30,0:05:42.90,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这就是所谓的 "Nina"
Dialogue: 1,0:05:42.90,0:05:49.30,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}the name Nina comes from Al Hirschfeld who's a uh he was a comic author in the US
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.90,0:05:49.30,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}"Nina"这个叫法来自Al Hirschfeld，他是美国的一位漫画家
Dialogue: 1,0:05:49.30,0:05:51.16,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and Nina is the name of his daughter
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.30,0:05:51.16,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}Nina是他女儿的名字
Dialogue: 1,0:05:51.16,0:05:57.04,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and here you can see the word Nina is actually hidden in the hair of this character three separate times
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.16,0:05:57.04,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}在这里你可以看到"Nina"这个词实际上是藏在这个人物的头发里的，有三个地方
Dialogue: 1,0:05:57.04,0:05:58.84,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you can see the N-I-N-A
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.04,0:05:58.84,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你可以看到N-I-N-A的字母
Dialogue: 1,0:05:58.84,0:06:06.32,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and he signs his name with a little 3 next to it indicating that there are three Ninas hidden in this one particular comic
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.84,0:06:06.32,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}他在署名的时候在旁边加了个小的数字3，表面这个漫画中藏了3个"Nina"
Dialogue: 1,0:06:06.32,0:06:10.29,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and he did this throughout his career after his daughter was born
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.32,0:06:10.29,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}在他整个职业生涯中，自从他女儿出生之后他都是如此做的
Dialogue: 1,0:06:10.29,0:06:16.95,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and so Ninas are essentially the untracked secrets or easter eggs of UK crosswords
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.29,0:06:16.95,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以"Nina"本质上是英国填字游戏中隐藏着的秘密或者说彩蛋
Dialogue: 1,0:06:16.95,0:06:19.89,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and one feature of them that's very notable is that they are missable
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.95,0:06:19.89,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它们的一个显著特点是，它们是"可错过的"
Dialogue: 1,0:06:19.89,0:06:24.69,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you could go through this entire crossword solve the whole thing think you were done and not even realize there was something there
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.89,0:06:24.69,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你可能把整个填字游戏解出来了，觉得自己做完了，甚至都没有意识到那你还有什么东西
Dialogue: 1,0:06:24.69,0:06:28.08,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh is this a problem or is it a feature
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.69,0:06:28.08,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那这算是个缺点还是特性呢？
Dialogue: 1,0:06:28.08,0:06:35.70,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh well I mean one issue with it being missable is sort of that eureka moment is just not going to be experienced by the whole audience of this puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.08,0:06:35.70,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这种"可错过的"东西所带来的一个问题是，它对应的尤里卡时刻是没法被所有玩家都体验到的
Dialogue: 1,0:06:35.70,0:06:40.50,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but on the other hand, the fact that the secret is missable somehow makes it more valuable
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.70,0:06:40.50,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但另一方面，这个秘密是"可错过的"这一点，在某种程度上又使它本身更有价值
Dialogue: 1,0:06:40.50,0:06:49.91,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it creates uh this feeling whenever you're solving one of these this author's puzzles let's say that there might just always be something lurking around the corner
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.50,0:06:49.91,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它创造了这样一种感觉，每当你在做这个作者的谜题时，总会觉得在角落里会藏着什么东西
Dialogue: 1,0:06:49.91,0:06:52.34,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and when you do find it it's more of a surprise
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.91,0:06:52.34,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而当你找到它的时候就会有更多的惊喜
Dialogue: 1,0:06:52.34,0:06:59.76,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and as we learned earlier that the sort of more surprising or unexpected something is the more exciting it is the more dopaminergic it is the the more sparkle is there
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.34,0:06:59.76,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而正如前面学到的，越是令人惊讶或意外的东西，\N 就越令人兴奋、有越高多巴胺能、有更多Sparkle
Dialogue: 1,0:06:59.76,0:07:07.06,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, the fact that the secrets are missable provides uh sort of additional excitement when you do find it
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.76,0:07:07.06,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，秘密是可错过的这一点会让你在解开它的时候有额外的兴奋
Dialogue: 1,0:07:07.06,0:07:14.55,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um another thing that missable secrets can do especially in video games is they can provide a reason to sort of go back to an old game
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.06,0:07:14.55,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}可错过的秘密能做到的另一件事是，特别是在电子游戏中，它能提供一个回去玩老游戏的原因
Dialogue: 1,0:07:14.55,0:07:19.16,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh like if I go back to a game like Chrono Trigger which is an RPG from the 90s
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.55,0:07:19.16,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}比如我回去玩《超时空之轮》这样的90年代的RPG
Dialogue: 1,0:07:19.16,0:07:23.96,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh there are things you can discover in that game that you didn't discover when you played it the first time
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.16,0:07:23.96,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你会发现一些你第一次玩的时候没发现的东西
Dialogue: 1,0:07:23.96,0:07:28.95,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}whether it's a line of dialogue or it's a sort of a hidden item that you just never knew was there
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.96,0:07:28.95,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}不论是一段对话或者某个隐藏物品，你之前不知道它的存在
Dialogue: 1,0:07:28.95,0:07:33.75,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}there are so many things and so much depth in a good rpg that you can play it multiple times
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.95,0:07:33.75,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}一个好的RPG里面有很多东西、很多深度，你可以反反复复玩
Dialogue: 1,0:07:33.75,0:07:40.92,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and I think some puzzle games like the Witness are starting to incorporate more and more of this into their games as well which is great
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.75,0:07:40.92,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我觉得一些解谜游戏，如《见证者》，也开始在里面融入更多这样的东西，这一点很不错
Dialogue: 1,0:07:40.92,0:07:45.72,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um lesson number 13 aporia is a promise of surprise
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.92,0:07:45.72,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}第13课「Aporia(困惑)是惊喜的前兆」
Dialogue: 1,0:07:45.72,0:07:52.56,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}aporia is a state when you're solving a puzzle where you as a solver believe that the puzzle is impossible
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.72,0:07:52.56,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}Aporia（困惑）是解谜时的一种状态，作为解谜者，你感觉这个谜题是不可能的
Dialogue: 1,0:07:52.56,0:07:55.44,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you may even feel like you have a proof that it's impossible
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.56,0:07:55.44,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}甚至感觉自己能找到证据证明它是不可能的
Dialogue: 1,0:07:55.44,0:07:58.71,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I need to do this… but there's a catch! I just can't
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.44,0:07:58.71,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}“我需要这样做...但有个难点！我做不到”
Dialogue: 1,0:07:58.71,0:08:01.40,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}what's the trick?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.71,0:08:01.40,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}“这里面有什么诀窍？”
Dialogue: 1,0:08:01.40,0:08:03.70,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um this may also be called a “known unknown”
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.40,0:08:03.70,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这也可以被称作“已知的未知”
Dialogue: 1,0:08:03.70,0:08:07.73,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}where you as a solver know that there is something that you don't know
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.70,0:08:07.73,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}作为一个解谜者，你知道有一些你不知道的东西
Dialogue: 1,0:08:07.73,0:08:17.46,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you think that ah well I mean this this puzzle is in this game or this person has you know built and shipped this puzzle to me which I have in my hands it must have a solution
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.73,0:08:17.46,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你会觉得既然这个谜题已经摆在我面前了，那总能解得出来吧
Dialogue: 1,0:08:17.46,0:08:22.32,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and yet I convinced myself that I believe it has no solution
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.46,0:08:22.32,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但我总还是相信这东西解不出来
Dialogue: 1,0:08:22.32,0:08:29.30,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh an example a simple example is with this puzzle here uh that I created uh
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.32,0:08:29.30,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}举一个简单的例子，这是我制作的一个谜题。
Dialogue: 1,0:08:29.30,0:08:31.09,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I’ll show you how it works
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.30,0:08:31.09,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我给你看看它怎么玩的
Dialogue: 1,0:08:31.09,0:08:33.78,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh let's switch to the full cam um
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.09,0:08:33.78,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}让我切下摄像头
Dialogue: 1,0:08:33.78,0:08:36.53,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}this object right here we'll call the cage
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.78,0:08:36.53,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这个东西，我把它叫做“笼子”
Dialogue: 1,0:08:36.53,0:08:39.54,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and there are two other parts which I will call A and B
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.53,0:08:39.54,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}还有另外两个部分，我称之为A和B
Dialogue: 1,0:08:39.54,0:08:44.21,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}here's A it's sort of got the L-shaped Tetris piece connected to the S-shape
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.54,0:08:44.21,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是A，它有点像L型的俄罗斯方块跟S型的连在一起
Dialogue: 1,0:08:44.21,0:08:48.44,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and this is B. B sort of has this three-way junction up near the top
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.21,0:08:48.44,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是B，B的顶部有个像三通一样形状
Dialogue: 1,0:08:48.44,0:08:51.57,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and the goal is to sort of put A and B into the cage
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.44,0:08:51.57,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}目标是把A和B插入“笼子”
Dialogue: 1,0:08:51.57,0:08:55.48,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and well let's just slide A in you can kind of put it in like that
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.57,0:08:55.48,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}让我们把A放进去，你可以像这样把它放进去
Dialogue: 1,0:08:55.48,0:08:58.55,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and that's the only place it goes it's very easy to see that
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.48,0:08:58.55,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是它唯一能放的地方，很容易看出来
Dialogue: 1,0:08:58.55,0:08:59.76,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and then you try and put b in
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.55,0:08:59.76,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后你试着把B放进去
Dialogue: 1,0:08:59.76,0:09:03.54,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and it just like it won't fit. there's not enough room to slide it in
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.76,0:09:03.54,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后它就放不进去了，没有足够的空间
Dialogue: 1,0:09:03.54,0:09:06.23,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh you could try putting it in from the bottom it
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.54,0:09:06.23,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你可以试着从底部把它放进去
Dialogue: 1,0:09:06.23,0:09:08.60,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}there's no room to put it in there either
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.23,0:09:08.60,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那里也没有空间可以放进去
Dialogue: 1,0:09:08.60,0:09:12.31,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}okay well maybe you don't put A in first. Maybe you have to put B in first
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.60,0:09:12.31,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}好吧，可能不能先把A放进去，也许得先把B放进去
